Question 1

set.seed(1108)

poll <- tibble(
  vote_gop = rbinom(n = 1000,
                    size = 1,
                    prob = .53))

Bootstrapping First Way

firstway_boot <- poll |> 
  rep_sample_n(size = 100, 
               replace = TRUE, 
               reps = 1000) |> 
  group_by(replicate) |> 
  summarize(prop_gop = mean(vote_gop)) 
quantile(firstway_boot$prop_gop, c(.025, .975))
 2.5% 97.5% 
 0.41  0.61

This first method gives me a 95% percentile-based confidence interval of (0.41 and 0.61).

Bootstrapping Second Way

secondway_boot <- poll |> 
  specify(response = vote_gop) |>   
  generate(reps = 1000) |> 
  calculate(stat = "mean")

Question 4

set.seed(10)

confidence_rap2 <- uno_songs |> 
  rep_sample_n(size = 25, replace = TRUE, reps = 1000) |> 
  group_by(replicate) |> 
  summarize(mean_year = mean(year))

    2.5%    97.5% 
1991.640 1998.001

The lower bound is 1992 and the upper bound is 1998. The conference interval here is larger or wider than the confidence interval from question 3 because the sample size is smaller. The smaller the sample size, the more variation there is.

Question 6

set.seed(22)

sampled_proportions <- c()

for (i in 1:1000) {
  
  sampled_results <- sample(c("aw", "hw" , "d"), 
                            size = 380,
                            replace = TRUE, 
                            prob = c(1/3,1/3,1/3))
  prop <- sum(sampled_results == "hw")/380
  sampled_proportions[i] <- prop
  
}
proportions_mapdf <- data.frame(Proportion = sampled_proportions)
proportions_graph <- ggplot(proportions_mapdf,
                            aes(x = Proportion)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01, boundary = 0.1, color = "navy") +
  labs(title = "Proportions with Equal Probability Results",
       x = "The Proportion",
       y = "Number of Proportions")
proportions_graph

I would say the histogram above roughly represents a ânormalâ distribution, as we see a bell-shaped histogram. This is a result of our large sample size. Based on our proportion in question 5, we have a smaller proportion here than the one above, meaning we can assume that home wins are actually more probable.

Question 7

proportions_mapdf |> 
  summarize(mean_hw = (mean(proportions)))
Warning: There was 1 warning in `summarize()`.

Caused by warning in `mean.default()`:
! argument is not numeric or logical: returning NA
  mean_hw
1      NA

A null hypothesis represents a hypothesus that has no effect or no relationship between variables. An alternative hypothesis has an effect or relationship in the population. In this case, the null hypothesis is that there isnât a difference in the proportion of home wins compared to loses or draws, or the relationship is the same. This is what we see in question 6. However, in question 5 we see what an alternative hypothesis looks like, where the home and away teams win at different rates, typically the home team having higher winning rates.

Question 8

The p-value is a measure to test the strength of evidence against a null hypothesis. In this scenario, the p-value is the probability that home wins is just as or more extreme than the proportion of away wins or draws (ties) when we assume all three possible results are equally probable and the relationship is the same.
